John Wiley & Sons, Inc. (NYSE: JWA) is a global publisher of print and electronic products, providing content and solutions to customers worldwide. The Company's core businesses produce professional and consumer books and subscription products; scientific, technical, medical and scholarly… MoreJohn Wiley & Sons, Inc. (NYSE: JWA) is a global publisher of print and electronic products, providing content and solutions to customers worldwide. The Company's core businesses produce professional and consumer books and subscription products; scientific, technical, medical and scholarly journals, encyclopedias, books, and online products; and textbooks and educational materials.

The John Wiley & Sons has previously acquired a number of companies, including, Inscape Holdings, and Efficient Learning Systems.
John Wiley & Sons, Inc. (NYSE: JWA) is a global publisher of print and electronic products, providing content and solutions to customers worldwide. The Company's core businesses produce professional and consumer books and subscription products; scientific, technical, medical and scholarly… MoreJohn Wiley & Sons, Inc. (NYSE: JWA) is a global publisher of print and electronic products, providing content and solutions to customers worldwide. The Company's core businesses produce professional and consumer books and subscription products; scientific, technical, medical and scholarly journals, encyclopedias, books, and online products; and textbooks and educational materials.

The John Wiley & Sons has previously acquired a number of companies, including, Inscape Holdings, and Efficient Learning Systems.

John Wiley & Sons' IT department is responsible for the oversight of all data security across the enterprise, and for enterprise information security resources and planning for the company. 

Technology for the company is overseen by a Chief Technology Officer. 

The company will places a focus on increase in expanding and enhancing its mobility environment for its presence in the eReader and eBook market.

The systems development group is responsible for telecommunications and network services for corporate locations. The group also maintains the technical services functions for desktop computers, and is responsible for server support function hosted on a UNIX platform. Teams are also responsible for the development, implementation, and support of the company's corporate applications. 

The Enterprise Technology Services (ETS group) handle the database administration, and related systems functions at the company.

The company has several IT directors who oversees responsibilities like, Global Business Intelligence Solutions,  HRIS, systems, publishing technology, network services, WAN Performance, application service and database technology.

John Wiley has a history of outsourcing its IT needs, including a long-standing relationship with provider MindTree, which manages Wiley's information technology needs in Bangalore, India, and in Australia. MindTree manages portions of infrastructure operations, business intelligence, and support for a variety of business systems. 

John Wiley & Sons, Inc.'s organization-wide data volume is approximately 100 TB – 1 PB and is growing at an annual rate of >50%.  Its data environment consists of highly fragmented data that is primarily deployed on premises in a purpose-built appliance.  The company uses relational database to store data primarily sourced from enterprise applications.

John Wiley & Sons, Inc. uses a NAS environment to back up its file data. It uses Native Snapshot and Replication as its main backup application. Its daily and weekly total data backup is 150TB and 150TB respectively.

The IT budget is typically finalized in Q3.

IT Intelligence Snippets

2012
John Wiley & Sons, Inc. describes data replication times as its biggest storage headache. Its top storage pain points are WAN being too slow, compliance issues, and the lack of modernizing/virtualizing solutions for systems and tape that are no longer viable. 

John Wiley & Sons, Inc. is hoping to deploy total data transformation in the near future.  The company is currently investing heavily in storage, servers, and development costs solutions.

John Wiley & Sons, Inc. was looking to deploy mobile application solutions over the subsequent 12 months. It also is planning to deploy cloud based services for applications and infrastructure during this time frame, but has no plans for new cloud platforms. The priority is on using cloud services for email, collaboration and conferencing, with the benefit of being able to free up additional IT resources for inhouse projects and systems, ones that need to stay in house. Sources at John Wiley & Sons, Inc. indicate the company's file transfers and data replication solutions cause the most strain on its network environment. 

 Senior sources at John Wiley & Sons indicate that perimeter security, mobile access, and inter-site communication will be priorities for its security efforts over the coming 12 months.

Over the next 12 month, the company is looking to deploy private cloud storage.







2013:
•100 tb – 1 pb data volume company-wide across 2 to 5 data centers, and expects an annual data growth of >50%.
•75-90% of its servers are to be virtualized by the end of 2013. 
•Corporate IT manages 2000 mobile devices, while 6000 are managed elsewhere. 
•Corporate IT manages 6000 desktops. 
•Standardized on 1-2 product vendors with a limited set of hardware. 
•Data center strategy is centered on standardizing on rack-mount x86 systems and virtualized servers, and moving applications to the public cloud (IaaS).
•Long term plan for running new applications is to rely on SaaS.





